South African futures were lower on Friday, after the JSE all share closed lower on softer mining stocks.The all share came back in late afternoon trade from a weak opening. Firmer retail, banking and financial shares could not, however, lift the all share into positive territory as miners remained under pressure due to the stronger dollar.The all share closed 0.36% lower at 51,708.60 points and the blue-chip top 40 lost 0.45%. General retailers and food and drug retailers rose 0.93%, respectively, with property ending the day up 0.89%. Banks rose 0.74% and financials gained 0.58%. Platinum lost 2.39% and the gold index shed 2.26%. Resources were down 1.15%.The all share was up 0.19% for the week and has gained 2.08% so far this year.The Dow Jones industrial average was down 0.12% in early evening trade with European markets mixed. The FTSE 100 was down 0.19% but the French CAC 40 added 0.44%.Brent crude rose 0.69% to $55.43 a barrel.At 5.47pm, the local near-dated top-40 Alsi futures index was 0.48% lower at 44,534 points, with 28,716 contracts traded from Thursday&rsquo;s 21,354.